  "risks": [{
    "id": "soil",
    "text": "90% of Robusta farmers apply mulch, compared to about half of Arabica farmers. This high percentage is likely because most Robusta farmers sell their coffee as dry cherry, and the cooperatives or mills that perform the hulling return the husks to them at no cost, allowing them to apply the coffee byproducts on their farms directly or after composting. Arabica farmers primarily sell their coffee as dry parchment or cherry. Those that depulp their coffee onsite often either mix the pulp with manure to make compost or bury it for several days before applying it to their farms. Another reason for the higher rate of mulching in Robusta areas may be the lower reliance on herbicides for weed management.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "water",
    "text": "While farmer organisations are increasingly encouraging Tanzanian Arabica farmers to sell their coffee as cherry and perform processing at cooperative-owned wet mills, where quality can be controlled more effectively, around 75% of Arabica farmers currently sell their coffee as dry parchment. Most of those farmers process their coffee on the farm, often using traditional hand depulpers and nearby water bodies or buckets for washing and fermentation. It is comparatively rare for Tanzania’s Robusta farmers to wet process their coffee, since most (84%) sell it as dry cherry. Of the farmers who process their coffee onsite, most pour the wastewater onto the ground or into a water body without treating it.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "climate_change",
    "text": "Deforestation by coffee farmers is rare in Tanzania. Among the limited number of farmers (less than 5%) that have cut down forest trees to clear land for coffee in the past 15 years, few report having received clearance from government officials before doing so. Around 80% of Arabica and Robusta farmers also have shade trees on their coffee plots, in addition to food trees. The most common shade tree species on Arabica farms are Syzygium cuminii, Cordia africana and Ficus natelensis; Robusta farmers most commonly have Maesopsis eminii and a few report Grevillea, a species mainly used for timber.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "gender_youth_equality",
    "text": "Nine out of ten Arabica and Robusta farmers want their children to continue with coffee farming, but only about seven in ten believe that they will follow in this path. Discouraging factors include rising production costs, such as increasing fertiliser prices. Qualitatively, farmers spoke of the benefits of existing initiatives and programs that target youth with opportunities to learn about and participate in coffee farming.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "child_labour",
    "text": "There is minimal risk of children under the legal working age of 14 being employed on Tanzanian coffee farms. On Arabica farms, which are on average larger than Robusta farms, there were reports of children under 14 looking for work on coffee farms during weekends and school holidays; however, the majority of farmers are hesitant to employ them because they know it is illegal. About 10% of Arabica and Robusta farmers with school-aged children report that their children help with coffee farming activities, but there is minimal risk of this interfering with their schooling. This may be the result of the Tanzanian government’s emphasis on prioritizing education for children, as well as training sessions run by farmer groups in some areas highlighting the negative effects of child labour.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "working_conditions",
    "text": "About half of Arabica farmers and four in ten Robusta farmers hire labour to help with coffee farming. Harvesting is the most common activity for which farmers hire labour; typically workers are paid per volume of cherry picked, and most receive at least the daily minimum wage of approximately US $1.60 (TZS 3,846.5). Nearly 90% of Arabica farmers that hire labour pay their workers at least the daily minimum wage for all activities, compared to less than 60% of Robusta farmers. Signs of forced labour are negligible in Tanzania. Access to clean drinking water for workers is an issue on both Arabica and Robusta farms. The most common water sources include springs, natural flowing sources, boreholes and water from the house.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "farm_management",
    "text": "Recordkeeping is more common amongst Arabica than Robusta farmers. About a fifth of Arabica farmers but only 3% of Robusta farmers keep records of their coffee-growing expenses. Half of Arabica farmers keep records of coffee sales, compared to a third of Robusta farmers. This difference is likely due to the fact that Arabica farmers often must wait longer to receive payment for their coffee, so they use these records to check payments received against the coffee they delivered several months earlier. The majority of farmers have access to a bank account or mobile money account. This is likely encouraged by the fact that cooperatives often pay farmers through these accounts. Around 80% of Arabica and Robusta farmers have not received any training or technical assistance within the past two years.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "yield_improvement",
    "text": "Productivity is low in Tanzania, with median yields of 249 kg GBE per ha for Arabica farmers and 411 kg GBE per ha for Robusta farmers. Farms tend to be small (the median sizes are 0.8 ha for Arabica farmers and 0.3 ha for Robusta farmers) and tree densities vary greatly between Arabica and Robusta farms, with a median of 2,128 trees per ha in Arabica regions and 659 in Robusta regions. Nearly 80% of Arabica and 90% of Robusta farmers have trees older than ten years old on their farms. Most farmers prune their coffee trees, with branch removal, desuckering and selective pruning reported as the most commonly used methods. Stumping is more common on Arabica farms (69%) than on Robusta farms (44%).",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "income_diversification",
    "text": "About half of Arabica farmers and a third of Robusta farmers in Tanzania rely on coffee for at least half their income, while 28% of Arabica and 9% of Robusta farmers depend economically entirely on coffee. Among those farmers that consider coffee their main income source, the most common secondary sources of income are food crops, livestock and agriculture businesses. Robusta farmers are more likely to rely on food crops, namely bananas, as their main income source. Two-thirds of Robusta and Arabica farmers live below the US $3.10/day poverty line.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }]
