  "risks": [{
    "id": "soil",
    "text": "Over 95% of coffee farms in Honduras are situated in areas with steep slopes, yet few farmers take sufficient measures to prevent soil erosion. This is likely due to lack of knowledge about these practices and the high cost of implementing them. On two out of five farms on sloped terrain, the farmers have not adopted any techniques to prevent erosion. Farmers are generally unaware of the benefits of increasing soil organic matter levels. 37% of farmers use mulch on more than half of the farm, but mostly it is only under shade trees (fallen leaves). There is an opportunity to increase composting rates by promoting composting of coffee byproducts: while two-thirds of farmers report depulping their coffee on-farm, only 5% compost it to use as organic fertiliser.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "water",
    "text": "56% of farms have a water body nearby, but two-thirds of these fail to maintain a buffer of at least five metres of vegetation between the farm’s crops and the water body. As many have small plots, farmers tend to maximise their land for coffee production without regard for maintaining an adequate buffer zone. Using water for irrigation is not a common practice, but two-thirds of farmers depulp and wash their coffee onsite. They typically lack access to water-efficient machinery for processing, and instead use traditional pulping machines that consume large amounts of water.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "climate_change",
    "text": "Most coffee in Honduras is not grown near protected areas. 98% of farms did not show any signs of deforestation during the 2021–2022 harvest period. On the farms that did show signs of recent deforestation, trees had not been cut near protected areas or in primary forest, and in nearly all cases the farmers had received authorisation from the relevant authorities. Most of the coffee produced in Honduras is shade-grown. Farmers have on average two tree species for shade on their farms, with popular choices being tropical fruits, ingas and other native and exotic shade species. At higher altitudes (above 1,300 metres), light shade is more commonly used as farmers believe it helps decrease the incidence of pests and diseases, such as American leaf spot. Farmers that use tropical fruit trees for shade (93%) also benefit from the additional source of income; banana and citrus trees are commonly intercropped with coffee.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "gender_youth_equality",
    "text": "Farmers in Honduras are optimistic about the future of coffee farming in the country. When asked about their future plans, 98% said they plan to continue coffee farming, and 90% expressed a hope that their children would also enter the family coffee business.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "child_labour",
    "text": "There is an increased risk of child labour on coffee farms in Honduras. Minors are involved in the country’s farming activities, especially during the harvest season. 70% of farmers that hire labour report a risk that workers bring children to work with them. There are reported risks of minors performing activities on the farm that are considered dangerous, with the most common activity being carrying heavy items, followed by operating machinery.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "working_conditions",
    "text": "86% of coffee farmers in Honduras hire labour for harvesting, spraying or weeding. A third of these farmers hire workers for all three activities during the year. Harvest workers are mostly paid by volume and, given the high demand for labour during the harvest season, usually receive at least the minimum wage. However, activities like spraying and weeding are done sporadically throughout the year, when labour is more abundant. Small farms (under 0.5 ha) typically rely on family labour to perform these activities, while larger farms are more likely to hire workers. Most farmers pay by time for spraying and weeding, and more than half of workers hired for these tasks receive below the legal minimum wage of approximately US $9.60 (HNL 230) per day. Outside of the harvest period, it is common for workers to accept the local ‘going rate’ for a day’s worth of work, which can often be below the minimum wage.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "farm_management",
    "text": "Very few farmers keep records of all farm activities. 70% receive sales receipts, which farmers need to reclaim some or all of the amount that IHCAFE automatically retains for each quintal of green coffee sold to be used for repayment of outstanding loans. However, only 10% of farmers keep expense records and 7% keep their own records of sales. Comprehensive recordkeeping is uncommon because most farmers do not see their farm as a business in the traditional sense.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "yield_improvement",
    "text": "The median yield in Honduras dropped 27% between the 2018–2019 and 2021–2022 harvests, to 674 kg green bean equivalent (GBE) per productive ha. While Honduras remains one of the more productive coffee-producing countries in Central America, this is much lower than Costa Rica’s median of 921 kg GBE per ha. Decreasing productivity and low coffee prices in recent years have not encouraged farmers to make on-farm investments, such as replanting or rejuvenating their coffee plots, that would increase productivity in the long term; however, the increase in prices since spring 2021 may incentivise such measures.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "income_diversification",
    "text": "Coffee farmers in Honduras have limited options for income diversification. Around half of farmers supplement their earnings from coffee with secondary sources of income such as day labour, subsistence food crops (including tropical fruit trees intercropped with their coffee plants) and remittances, which currently account for about 20% of the country’s GDP and are the main source of foreign exchange. However, despite the fact that coffee yields have been going down while costs have gone up in recent years, 71% of farmers still rely on coffee as their primary source of income. While the median annual income from coffee is only US $2,003, because most farms have steep slopes there is little opportunity to grow other cash crops. In addition, most farms are small (the average farm size is 2.2 ha), so opportunity to expand crops and crop area is restricted.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }]
