  "risks": [{
    "id": "soil",
    "text": "Nine out of ten coffee farms in Peru are on sloped terrain, but just 6% of the farmers whose coffee plots are on slopes implement the recommended three or more erosion control measures. 18% do not take any measures to prevent erosion, and the remainder use one or two methods – most commonly mulch, natural barriers and/or contour planting. Factors contributing to the limited implementation of sufficient erosion control practices likely include lack of knowledge about these practices and the associated costs.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "water",
    "text": "Farmers in Peru typically view water as an abundant resource that does not require conservation. Just 5% of coffee farmers in Peru use water for irrigation, but nearly all wet process their coffee on the farm. Of those farmers who wash their coffee onsite, the vast majority do not have water-efficient machines, such as ecopulpers or water recirculation systems, nor do they monitor water consumption.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "climate_change",
    "text": "There is a high risk of deforestation on coffee farms in Peru, with 15% of farmers reporting cutting down forest trees since 2005 in non-protected areas to establish or expand their coffee farms. This risk is more acute in certain areas of the departments of San Martín and Junín, specifically in southeast San Martín (55%), east Satipo (33%), west Satipo (29%) and Moyobamba (25%). Most farmers who have cut down forest trees have done so without authorisation from the proper authorities, or on land to which they do not have legal title. These farms tend to be in more remote, mountainous areas with less government or local authority presence.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "gender_youth_equality",
    "text": "Farmers in Peru are fairly optimistic about the future of coffee farming. 97% say they plan to continue farming coffee in the future, and two-thirds expect their children to continue the legacy.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "child_labour",
    "text": "There is a risk of child labour in Peru, and on 4% of farms there is a risk of this work interfering with children’s access to education. The risk of farmers directly hiring minors under the legal minimum working age of 14 is negligible; most of the risk of child labour stems from workers bringing their children to the farm with them to help harvest cherries. This is perceived by farming communities as safer than leaving children at home alone, and also helps rural families earn additional income.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "working_conditions",
    "text": "71% of farmers in Peru hire labour, most commonly for harvesting or spraying but sometimes also for weeding. In general, there is very little risk of forced or coercive labour practices in Peru’s supply chain. Although the national minimum wage for the agriculture sector rose by 9% in 2022, to US $8.614(PEN 33.06) per day), farmers who hired workers during the 2021–2022 harvest period almost universally met the minimum wage. For harvesting and weeding, the daily rate ranges between US $9 and $13 (PEN 34.56 and 49.92). Minimum wage compliance has increased since the 2020–2021 harvest period (from 80% to 98%), due to workers demanding higher wages when coffee prices rise and to labour shortages: two-fifths of farmers who hire labour reported difficulty finding harvest workers during the 2021–2022 coffee harvest.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "farm_management",
    "text": "Few farmers keep records of all farm activities. About a third keep records of sales. A quarter of farmers keep records of expenses, and less than one in five keep records of profits. Many farmers do not keep comprehensive records because they do see their farms as businesses in the traditional sense. Two-thirds of the country’s coffee farmers have not had any training sessions or technical assistance visits in the last two years, and only about one in five farmers have received sufficient training. Peruvian coffee farmers do not benefit from strong institutional support of the type provided in other origins in Latin America, where farmers often receive assistance through national coffee institutes. Half of Peru’s coffee farmers do not have a bank account, and two-thirds of farmers do not have access to credit. A third of farmers that have loans show signs of overindebtedness, such as difficulty repaying their loans, using a large portion of the income from their coffee harvest to pay off debt or having multiple loans.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "yield_improvement",
    "text": "The median yield of coffee farmers in Peru is 597 kg green bean equivalent (GBE) per productive ha, which is lower than the best practice level of 750 kg GBE per ha. One key factor contributing to lower productivity is likely the high incidence of pests and diseases, and inadequate management of these problems. 94% of farmers in Peru report issues with pests or diseases on their farms, with the most common problems being leaf rust (71%), American leaf spot (40%) and coffee berry borer (38%). However, only a third of farmers use an integrated pest management (IPM) approach, combining at least three techniques. Furthermore, while a third of farmers have rust-resistant varieties on their farms, many report that their resistance has been dwindling in recent years and varieties that used to ward off leaf rust are now becoming infected with the disease.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "income_diversification",
    "text": "Three-quarters of Peruvian coffee farmers rely on coffee as their primary source of income, but as most farms are small, yields are relatively low and few farmers (15%) receive a dividend or second payment for their coffee, the median annual income from coffee is low, at US $3,516. 40% of farmers supplement their earnings from coffee with secondary sources of income such as raising food crops, cash crops (such as cacao) or livestock, or working as day labourers.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }]
