  "risks": [{
    "id": "soil",
    "text": "While most of Colombia’s coffee grows in mountainous regions, close to a third of farmers do not report implementing any erosion control methods on sloped terrain, mainly because they don’t consider their farms to be at high risk of erosion. For farmers that report taking actions to prevent soil degradation, stabilising grasses, natural barriers and dikes are the most commonly used methods. The use of mulch and cover crops, whether to prevent erosion or to increase soil organic matter content, is uncommon among Colombian farmers. Though farmers may be aware of the benefits of mulching, they view it as unnecessary when coffee pulp is applied as compost (a practice reported by 40% of farmers).",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "water",
    "text": "Nearly all farmers in Colombia have a wet mill onsite to process their coffee, which is predominantly sold as dry or wet parchment. Due to their high cost, the majority of farmers do not have water-efficient machines such as ecopulpers, demucilagers or water recirculation systems, nor do they monitor water consumption.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "climate_change",
    "text": "Close to a third of Colombian farmers grow their coffee under a canopy of diverse shade trees. Farming and geographic differences contribute to some regions having a higher share of farms with shade-grown coffee than others. In Santander, for example, there is a history of agroforesty farming practices and about 70% of farms have sufficient shade. In contrast, in departments like Caldas and Huila, where farmers have historically favoured high coffee tree density and maximal sunlight exposure aimed at increasing yields, this share is 20% of farms.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "gender_youth_equality",
    "text": "About half of farmers with children expect them to continue with coffee farming. However, the migration of younger generations to rapidly growing metropolitan areas poses a risk to the effective transfer of agricultural activities and knowledge to the next generation. This is especially true in Cundinamarca (home to Bogotá, the country’s capital and largest city), where 56% of farmers – the highest share in any region – do not believe that their children will continue coffee farming.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "child_labour",
    "text": "The risk of children under the age of 15 (the legal minimum working age in Colombia) working on coffee farms is low (3%), and mainly stems from workers bringing their children to the farm with them to help pick cherries during the harvest as a way to increase the family’s earnings.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "working_conditions",
    "text": "60% of farmers report using pesticides, a share that is consistent with previous harvest years. On farms where agrochemicals are used, approximately 10% of farmers report use of the full set of recommended PPE (face mask, safety goggles and gloves) for spraying chemicals, with hot weather and discomfort usually cited as the main reasons for not wearing the complete set. A similar share of farmers report that they or the workers they have hired for spraying have received training on safe handling of pesticides, which is consistent with low access to training across the country.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "farm_management",
    "text": "About a fifth of Colombian coffee farmers keep written records of sales, while 16% keep records of expenses for farm inputs. On average, these farmers have bigger coffee plots and more income from coffee per hectare than their peers who don’t keep written records. While cooperatives and other farmer organisations generally incentivize and train their members on recordkeeping, many farmers don’t have a clear understanding of how this can benefit them.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "yield_improvement",
    "text": "For the past two years, Colombia has experienced severe rainy seasons that have affected the coffee flowering cycle. As a result, the median yield for the 2021–2022 harvest year fell by 16% compared to the previous harvest year, from 667 kg GBE per ha to 563 kg GBE per ha. Farmers in Antioquia and Huila, which consistently rank as the top coffee-producing regions, saw yields of 834 kg and 688 kg per ha during the 2021–2022 harvest, aided by the application of higher quantities of inorganic fertiliser. Low-yielding regions include Cundinamarca and Cauca, where coffee farming is less input- and labour-intensive.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "income_diversification",
    "text": "Two-thirds of Colombian coffee farmers have two harvests per year, which contributes to 77% reporting that coffee is the household’s main source of income. Half of Colombia’s coffee farmers have alternative income streams, such as day-labouring jobs and other cash crops, often intercropped with coffee (commonly plantain or bananas).",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }]
