  "risks": [{
    "id": "soil",
    "text": "Most farmers do not apply agronomic best practices for soil improvement, with nearly 92% of Brazil’s Arabica farms on sloped terrain, farmers need to adopt practices for erosion control. A similar proportion of farmers (13%) utilise mulch, compost or cover crops to increase soil organic matter content, and with only 5% of farmers intercropping within their coffee plots there is little chance for organic matter from complementary crops to improve soil health.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "water",
    "text": "Brazil’s Arabica farmers are generally responsible regarding the management of water bodies: of the farms with a water body onsite, 97% maintain an adequate riparian buffer zone. Consequently, there is minimal (1%) risk of pollution of water bodies on Arabica farms. Depulping onsite is also uncommon; just 3% of Arabica farmers wet process their coffee on the farm.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "climate_change",
    "text": "There is a negligible risk of Arabica farmers deforesting to expand their coffee plots over the past 15 years, with a 3% risk of new land being cleared to grow coffee without a land permit or government authorisation. 85% of farmers report designating a portion of their land as an environmentally protected area (a legal requirement of Brazil’s Forest Code, and about a third comply with the nationally stipulated threshold of 20% of total farmland as a legal reserve.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "gender_youth_equality",
    "text": "Coffee has a special bond with the landscape, history and national culture of Brazil, which accounts for about a third of global production. Three in five of Brazil’s Arabica farmers believe their children will be coffee farmers too, and nearly three-quarters want them to continue coffee farming.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "child_labour",
    "text": "Child labour violations on Arabica farms in Brazil are rare. The farms are often large and established, and they exist within a professionally managed industry, so directly hiring minors is uncommon. There is a small risk of farmers’ children missing school to help on the family farm or working on the farm more than 14 hours during a school week, which is considered to be inappropriate for children younger than 13.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "working_conditions",
    "text": "There is minimal risk of forced labour or minimum wage violations on Brazil’s Arabica farms. However, it is worth noting the 310 cases of labour conditions analogous to slavery identified in the coffee sector by the Brazilian Labour Inspectorate in 2021 (up from 140 in 2020). Arabica coffee industry workers are paid well above the daily minimum wage of US $7.628 (BRL 40.40), at a median rate of US $19.25 (BRL 102) per day. This figure climbs as high as US $62.26 (BRL 330) in highly developed and more mechanised regions like Sul de Minas (in the southern part of Minas Gerais, the state that is responsible for nearly half of Brazil’s coffee production)",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "farm_management",
    "text": "Four out of five Brazilian Arabica farmers have access to processing facilities (such as wet mills or hulling stations) that allow them to improve the quality of their coffee and sell it at a higher price. Farmers also generally have a strong understanding of the coffee market and the potential value of their product. Despite this, only about half have access to training programmes or technical assistance. For example, over 80% of farmers in the centre and north of Sul de Minas – one of the country’s most developed coffee-growing areas – have access to training programmes, whereas that figure falls as low as 22% for farmers in other regions.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "yield_improvement",
    "text": "While Brazilian Arabica farms are typically highly mechanised, advanced and efficient, fewer than 15% of Arabica farmers implement an integrated pest and disease management approach (combining at least three methods). Only 3% monitor or scout pest and disease levels on their farms. Many farmers turn to chemical applications, particularly in light of recent outbreaks of leaf miner, which reproduces more quickly in hot and dry regions like the Cerrado. On average, farmers apply insecticides and fungicides about three times per year, and herbicides twice. Risk of banned pesticide use is minimal.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "income_diversification",
    "text": "Over half of Brazilian Arabica farmers derive all of their income from coffee, and another 28% say it accounts for more than half. Of those who supplement their income with other agricultural activities, common activities include growing corn, beans and avocado, while many raise cattle as well.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }]
