  "id": "Brazil_Robusta",
  "name": "Robusta",
  "isActive": true,
  "namePos": "left",
  "xPos": -100,
  "yPos": -100,
  "region": "Latin America",
  "projects": [],
  "risks": [{
    "id": "soil",
    "text": "Most Brazilian Robusta farmers do not take adequate measures to conserve or increase the levels of organic matter in their soil. Robusta usually grows at lower altitudes, in less mountainous regions: just over half of Brazil’s Robusta farms are on sloped terrain, compared to over 90% of Arabica farms. Of those farmers whose coffee plots are on slopes, 14% use the recommended three or more erosion control methods.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "water",
    "text": "Over 80% of Robusta farmers irrigate, compared to 4% of Arabica farmers. This difference is likely due in part to their greater focus on yields, as well as variations in growing conditions in the regions where Robusta and Arabica farms are concentrated. While irrigation may be seen as a sign of technological advancement and can boost productivity on the farm, it also leads to significant water use. Among the Robusta farmers that irrigate, just 8% track their water use, and a similar share either are within best practice range or are taking active measures to reduce their water use to within that range. Less than 1% of Robusta farmers wet process on their farms.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "climate_change",
    "text": "Enveritas found little risk of deforestation on Brazil’s Robusta farms over the past 15 years, with a 3% risk within that time frame of new land being cleared to grow coffee without a land permit or authorisation by the government. Two-thirds of farmers report designating a portion of their land as an environmentally protected area (a legal requirement of Brazil’s Forest Code), and about a third comply with the nationally stipulated threshold of 20% of total farmland as a legal reserve.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "gender_youth_equality",
    "text": "Given the long history and success of the coffee farming industry in Brazil, and the increased focus on Robusta in recent years, it is unsurprising that over half of Brazilian Robusta farmers believe their children will be coffee farmers too, and nearly three-quarters want them to continue coffee farming.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "child_labour",
    "text": "There is minimal risk of child labour violations on Brazilian coffee farms (both Robusta and Arabica). Robusta farms are often large and established and they exist within a professionally managed industry, so directly hiring minors is uncommon. There is a small risk of farmers’ children missing school to help on the family farm, typically on farms where children work more than 14 hours during a full school week.",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "working_conditions",
    "text": "The risk of forced labour or minimum wage violations on Brazil’s Robusta farms is also minimal. However, it is worth noting the 310 cases of labour conditions analogous to slavery identified in the coffee sector by the Brazilian Labour Inspectorate in 2021 (up from 140 in 2020). Similar to Arabica workers, Robusta workers are usually paid well above the daily minimum wage of US $7.629 (BRL 40.40), at a median rate of US $18.87 (BRL 100) per day",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "farm_management",
    "text": "Although some Robusta farmers keep financial records, it is not common practice. Just over a third keep sales records, and just under a third keep records of expenses. Of those who keep both sales and expense records, four in five use this information to calculate profit and loss. As with Arabica farmers, the difference in recordkeeping behaviour may be influenced by the size and prosperity of the farm: the average farm size of the farmers who keep both types of records is five times that of those who do not.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "yield_improvement",
    "text": "As Robusta farmers are overwhelmingly focused on production volumes, mitigating potential losses due to pests and diseases might be expected to be a top priority. Nevertheless, only 6% of farmers implement an integrated pest and disease management approach (combining three or more methods), and fewer than 1% monitor for pests and diseases. Chemical applications are frequent, though more common to control weeds than pests. Risk of banned pesticide use is minimal.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "income_diversification",
    "text": "A third of Brazilian Robusta farmers derive all of their income from coffee, and another 36% say it accounts for more than half. Most farmers who supplement their income from coffee with other sources rely on the sale of other crops, such as bananas, corn and cocoa, as a complement.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }]
