  "risks": [{
    "id": "soil",
    "text": "Decades of monocropping and intensive coffee cultivation have taken a toll on the health and fertility of the soil on Vietnamese coffee farms. Nearly all coffee farmers in the Central Highlands apply inorganic fertilisers to increase yields, almost exclusively basing their decisions about the quantity and type of fertiliser to use on local farming norms rather than analysis of the soil’s nutrient needs. 2% of farmers report adapting their fertiliser use based on the result of a recent soil or leaf test. The overuse of inorganic fertilisers, coupled with lower adoption of organic fertilisers (57%), threatens soil fertility.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "water",
    "text": "About 96% of coffee farms in Vietnam are irrigated, typically using hoses and pumps or, less frequently, fixed sprinklers. Farmers usually irrigate three times per year, and ground water is the main source. While four out of five farmers report tracking the quantity of water used for irrigation, on more than 90% of these farms the water consumption levels are not efficient or within local benchmark levels.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "climate_change",
    "text": "About a third of the farmers in the Central Highlands cite climate change as one their main challenges. Shade trees are present on nearly three-quarters of coffee farms and are most common in Dak Lak and Dak Nong, probably due to the high prevalence of intercropping on farms in these provinces. The main shade tree types are Senna siamea, Ceiba pentandra and acacia. Intercropping has become more popular since 2018, possibly as a response to volatile coffee prices; more than four out of five farmers across the Central Highlands intercrop on their farms, with fruit trees such as durian and avocado becoming increasingly popular choices over pepper.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "gender_youth_equality",
    "text": "The average age of coffee farmers in Vietnam is 48 years old. This is considerably higher than the median age of Vietnam’s population (32). About two-thirds of these farmers want their children to continue farming coffee, but only half think that they will. Vietnam’s rapid economic growth provides many opportunities in the manufacturing and technology sectors, enticing the young and educated to urban centres.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "child_labour",
    "text": "There is minimal risk of coffee farmers in Vietnam directly employing children under the legal working age of 15, or of the children of farmers missing school to help out on the farm. However, there is some risk of minors performing dangerous work on coffee farms. The highest risk was identified in Gia Lai (9%), probably due to a higher percentage of minorities in this province (52%).",
    "riskColor": "#2f75b5"
  }, {
    "id": "working_conditions",
    "text": "There is a risk of coercive labour practices, such as farmers withholding payments or retaining workers’ identity documents, on 5% of farms, rising to 15% in Lam Dong, where farmers are more likely to hire labourers from other provinces.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }, {
    "id": "farm_management",
    "text": "Training and Technical Assistance programs remain out of reach for most coffee farmers. About a quarter of farmers have received some form of training in the last two years, but just 5% have received sufficient training (which Enveritas defines as at least four sessions during a two-year period). Training is typically provided by agrochemical companies, government bodies and, to a lesser extent, farmer organisations. The focus is primarily on farming practices and coffee quality management.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "yield_improvement",
    "text": "The median yield reported by farmers across the Central Highlands is approximately 2,500 kg GBE per productive ha. Farmers in Lam Dong report the highest median yield, at 3,300 kg GBE per ha, while farmers in Gia Lai and Dak Lak report the lowest yields, at about 2,000 kg GBE per ha. While the high incidence of pests and diseases is a major challenge in Vietnam (nearly all farmers report experiencing problems with pests or diseases), just 13% of farmers use an integrated pest management (IPM) approach. 85% of farmers use chemicals to manage pests and diseases or weeds.",
    "riskColor": "#ffc000"
  }, {
    "id": "income_diversification",
    "text": "Coffee is a mainstay of Vietnam’s economy, accounting for 10% of the country’s agricultural export turnover and contributing 30% to the GDP in the Central Highlands. For about three-quarters of coffee farmers, coffee is the primary source of household income. For those farmers whose primary source of income is not coffee, other agricultural activities (such as growing cash crops or raising livestock), salaried jobs, working as day labourers and other non-agricultural businesses are the most common sources of income. Many coffee farmers also pursue one or more of those activities to diversify the sources of household income. In particular, growing other crops such as pepper, avocado and durian is a major source of revenue for many coffee farmers in Vietnam.",
    "riskColor": "#bdd7ee"
  }]
